This question involves calculations with large numbers, which corresponds to **Topic 1.1: Using standard form**. First, we express the given values in scientific notation ($a \times 10^k$) to make the multiplication easier.

$$
\begin{aligned} 
\text{Trees} &= 20 \text{ million} = 20,000,000 = 2 \times 10^7 \\ 
\text{Oxygen per tree} &= 50 \text{ kg} = 5 \times 10^1 \text{ kg} 
\end{aligned}
$$

The question requires the answer in tonnes. We know that $1 \text{ tonne} = 1000 \text{ kg} = 10^3 \text{ kg}$. To convert from kilograms to tonnes, we divide by $10^3$, which is equivalent to multiplying by $10^{-3}$.

Using the index rules again:

$$
\begin{aligned} 
\text{Total (tonnes)} &= (1.0 \times 10^9) \times 10^{-3} \\ 
&= 1.0 \times 10^{9 + (-3)} \\ 
&= 1.0 \times 10^{9-3} \\ 
&= 1.0 \times 10^6 \text{ tonnes} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Multiply the number of trees by the oxygen production per tree (in tonnes):

$$
\begin{aligned} 
\text{Total Oxygen} &= (2 \times 10^7) \times 0.05 \\ 
&= (2 \times 0.05) \times 10^7 \\ 
&= 0.1 \times 10^7 \\ 
&= 1 \times 10^6 \text{ tonnes} 
\end{aligned}
$$
